l favouritism towards the beef industry. The degree to which unorthodox links between political donations impacted on policy choices which exacerbated the depth of Ireland’s economic collapse is considered. This book will appeal to students and scholars of Irish politics, corruption theory, governance, public policy and political financing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAugustine Birrell.  aDublin Castle.  aFianna Fáil.  aIrish economic sovereignty.  aIrish independence.  aIrish party.  aNational Coalition government.  aTribunal trilogy.  abeef industry.  aclandestine influence.  aeconomic protectionalism policy.  aexport "as.  alegitimate entitlement.  ameritocracy.  aplanning permission.  apolitical corruption.  apolitical favouritism.  apost-independent Ireland.  aprivatisation process.  astate sponsored bodies.1 aByrne, Elaine A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779808440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847798084423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847798084/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles